ce:section.ce:para:
The developed CDs demonstrated excellent morphology and uniform particle distribution through FESEM and HRTEM images. Owing to their unique morphology, CDs exhibit promising application in the adsorptive removal of harmful toxin i.e. Allura red (Fig. S6). The emission behaviour of all the prepared CDs were tested in presence of different types of food colorant and azo dyes (Fig S6). Out of all chosen dyes, all the three types of prepared CDs show excellent selectivity towards Allura red in contrast to Bromophenol, Congo red, Erythrosine Extra Bluish, Sunset yellow, Nile red, Sudan I, Amaranth and Trypan blue. To further assess the sensitivity of the as synthesised adsorbents (C-CDs, P-CDs and M-CDs), the respective spectrophotometric and fluorometric titrations were carried out in presence of increasing concentrations of Allura red (0–30 μM). The fluorescence spectra demonstrate the sequential turn off behaviour of CDs as the emission intensity of all the chosen CDs were continued to decrease with increasing amount of Allura red (Fig. 3
                        (ai-aiii)). Nevertheless, UV–vis. absorption spectra represent enhancement in absorbance values from 0 to 30 μM concentration of Allura red (Fig. 3(bi-biii)). These complementary results of fluorescence and UV–vis. studies were comparable with the literature data (Shukla et al., 2019). The adsorption efficiency of CDs exhibits a good linear relationship with increased concentration of Allura red as given in stern volmer plots (Fig. 4
                        ). To investigate the interaction behavior of CDs with Allura red, the zeta potential measurements were carried out (Fig. S7). The pure CQDs have displayed the positive zeta potential values for C-CDs (0.23 mV), P-CDs (0.11 mV) and M-CDs (0.07 mV) which further supported the electrostatic interaction between the CDs and anionic dye (Allura red). These electrostatic forces of attractions between Allura red and CDs resulted in the formation of AR-CDs complex. In addition, the AR complex with C-CDs showed the zeta potential value as −0.11 as compared to +0.23 mV for pure C-CDs. These changes in the zeta potential measurement and overall negative charge over the surface of particles have further confirmed the effective adsorption of AR over the surface of CDs (Fig S7d). To further verify the adsorption of Allura red molecules over CDs surface, N2 adsorption–desorption analysis has been carried out for all the three types of CDs (Table S2). The data show that the C-CDs poses maximum surface area and pore volume compared to others formed particles. The developed AR-CDs complex (Allura red-carbon dots) showed a slight decrease in absorption value of UV light on increasing the concentration of Allura red due to enhanced interaction between CDs and non-fluorescent Allura red molecules. Fig. S10 represents the solutions with varied concentration of Allura red under visible and UV illumination. The quenching efficiency obtained in case of C-CDs, P-CDs, and M-CDs were found to be 94.10, 80.54, and 86.53 % respectively. The maximum quenching in case of C-CDs is strongly associated with the maximum vacant surface-active sites and pore volume in case of C-CDs which further enhanced its adsorption properties. On comparing their efficacy, it was estimated that C-CDs shows maximum detection limit (0.604) for Allura red in contrast to P-CDs (0.260) and M-CDs (0.166). However, the C-CDs exhibits minimum detection limits (0.078) when the concentration of adsorbent was reduced to half (Table S3). From the results, it was evident that C-CDs act as excellent adsorbent for Allura red at concentration of 0.5 mg/mL and temperature 298 K due to the reduction in standard deviation and slope values at lower concentration. The experimental results indicated that, increasing the concentration of absorbent decreases the limit of detection upto 8, 2, 1.5 folds in C-CDs, P-CDs and M-CDs respectively and increases the range of linearity to approximately 2 times (Fig. S8). Meanwhile, to verify the selectivity of CDs for Allura red, the emission spectra was obtained in presence of other dyes including Bromophenol, Congo red, Nile red, Erythrosine Extra Bluish, Amaranth, Sunset yellow, Sudan I, Trypan blue (Fig. S11). In this study, the concentration of other dyes was kept approximately twice the concentration of Allura red. The whole experiment was performed in three successive cycles and average results were plotted. The obtained results exhibit negligible effect induced by other dyes on the emission spectra of AR-CDs complex which further indicates that the developed CDs shows excellent selectivity and sensitivity towards Allura red (Fig. S8 and Fig. S11).
